
TY  - JOUR
T1  - ON EQUILIBRIUM FOR OVERLAPPING GENERATIONS ORGANIZATIONS*
AU  - Prescott, Edward C.
AU  - Ríos-Rull, José-Víctor
Y1  - 2005/11/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2005.00360.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1065
EP  - 1080
VL  - 46
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2005.00360.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Necessary conditions for equilibrium are that beliefs about the behavior of other agents are rational and individuals maximize. We argue that in stationary OLG environments this implies that any future generation in the same situation as the initial generation must do as well as the initial generation did in that situation. We conclude that the existing equilibrium concepts in the literature do not satisfy this condition. We then propose an alternative equilibrium concept, organizational equilibrium that satisfies this condition. We show that equilibrium exists, it is unique, and it improves over autarky without achieving optimality. Moreover, the equilibrium can be readily found by solving a maximization program.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - OPTIMAL FORECAST COMBINATION UNDER REGIME SWITCHING*
AU  - Elliott, Graham
AU  - Timmermann, Allan
Y1  - 2005/11/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2005.00361.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1081
EP  - 1102
VL  - 46
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2005.00361.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article proposes a new forecast combination method that lets the combination weights be driven by regime switching in a latent state variable. An empirical application that combines forecasts from survey data and time series models finds that the proposed regime switching combination scheme performs well for a variety of macroeconomic variables. Monte Carlo simulations shed light on the type of data-generating processes for which the proposed combination method can be expected to perform better than a range of alternative combination schemes. Finally, we show how time variations in the combination weights arise when the target variable and the predictors share a common factor structure driven by a hidden Markov process.
ER  - 

